\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\par

\pard\nowidctlpar When adding two (or more) rational expressions, the first step is to transform them so that they all have the same denominator. In principle, you don't have to find the least common denominator (LCD), any common denominator will do.  For example, say I want to add two rational expressions:  1/x^2 + 1/x. The LCD is clearly x^2. So we have \par
1/x^2+1/x = 1/x^2 + x/x^2 = (1+x)/x^2.  Now if I don't know how to find the LCD, I can just find the product of the two denominators and get a common denominator x^2*x=x^3. Using this I have 1/x^2 + 1/x = x/x^3 + x^2/x^3 = (x+x^2)/x^3.  Both are correct, but the latter can be further simplified by finding the GCF of the numerator and the denominator\par
GCF(x+x^2, x^3) = x. Hence (x+x^2)/x^3 = x(1+x)/ [x*x^2] = (1+x)/x^2.\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\par

