Two points that can be improved:\par
(1) There is no such thing as greatest common denominator. For example, consider 1/10 and 1/15. The common denominators of these two fractions are just the common multiple of 10 and 15, i.e., \{30, 60, 90,......\} all multiples of 30. So there is no greatest common denominator, what we need to find is the least common denominator, here 30 is the one.\par
\par
(2) The denominators of rational expressions may be polynomials, therefore common denominators may be polynomials instead of numbers.\par
\par
For example, I want to solve 2/(x+1) = 3/x.  The least common denominator is x(x+1) (not a number). So I multiply both sides by x(x+1):\par
2x(x+1)/(x+1) = 3x(x+1)/x ----> 2x = 3(x+1) ---> 2x = 3x + 3 ---> x = -3.\par
\par

