\pard\nowidctlpar I'm glad that you read the textbook very carefully. Here are my two cents: no step should be skipped; but when the problem is really simple or when you're very experienced with solving this type of problems, you can just do a mental check on certain step. I'll use Example (1a) on page 464 for discussion:\par
Solve: 5/3 = 4/x\par
Step1: LCD = 3x.\par
Step2: Multiply both sides by 3x --> 3*x*5/3 = 3*x*4/x  ---> 5x = 3*4\par
Step3: Simplify each term --> 5x = 12\par
Step4: Solve the resulting equation --> x = 12/5\par
Step5: Check the answer by plugging 12/5 for x in the original equation.  Left-hand-side = 5/3, right-hand-side=4/x = 4/(12/5) = 4*5/12 = 5/3= left-hand-side, check done. \par
\par
In the textbook, step 1-3 are combined which is only recommended when the problem is really simple for you.\par
