I agree that GCF and LCD are kind of confusing. Actually many people get them mixed.  To understand the concepts more clearly, we need to see the difference between factor and multiple. Let's say I have two polynomials P(x) = x and Q(x) =x(x+1); as an additional example I also have two integers A = 8 and B=16.\par
\par
Since Q(x) can be written as P(x) times another polynomial, we say x is a factor of x(x+1) equivalently, x(x+1) is a multiple of x.\par
\par
Similarly for the numbers, since B can be written as A times another integer, we say 8 is a factor of 16, equivalently, 16 is a multiple of 8.\par
\par
GCF means the greatest common factor. While LCD means the least common denominator, but it actually means the least common multiple of all denominators. \par
