You have described very clearly the way to simplify square root radicals. But a lot of times we're dealing with higher degree radicals. For example, you may be asked to simplify the cubic root of 81 or fourth-root of 64 etc. In those cases you will following essentially the same idea by breaking down the radicand into its perfect power numbers corresponding to the appropriate degree.  For example, to simplify the cubic-root of 81, we write 81=(3^3)*3, then get cubic-root(81) = 3*cubic-root(3). \par
\par

